# Week 1 — Nmap Commands

## What is Nmap?
Nmap (Network Mapper) is a tool used to discover open ports
and services on a target. It is the first tool used in almost
every penetration test.

## Commands I ran today

### nmap 172.17.0.2
Basic scan. Checks the top 1000 most common ports.
Found: Port 80 open (HTTP)

### nmap -sV 172.17.0.2
Service version scan. Identifies what software is running.
Found: Apache httpd 2.4.25 on Debian Linux
Why this matters: Apache 2.4.25 is from 2017 and has known CVEs.

### nmap -sV -oN reports/dvwa-nmap-scan.txt 172.17.0.2
Same scan but saves output to a file.
-oN means "output Normal format"
Always do this on real engagements — you need a record.

## Other important Nmap flags to remember
-sC  : runs default scripts (extra checks automatically)
-p-  : scans all 65535 ports not just top 1000
-A   : aggressive scan, combines -sV -sC and OS detection
-T4  : faster scan speed (T1=slowest, T5=fastest)

## Key lesson
Version numbers are critical. Knowing the software version
lets you search for known vulnerabilities (CVEs) against it.
Search: "Apache 2.4.25 CVE" on Google to see real vulnerabilities.